Performance considerations
--------------------------

The notes in the challenge document mention that robust implementations
handle more than 2 million numbers per 10-second in some specific machine
acting as server, but nothing is said about the clients or the kind of
network connecting them.

Note also that the time required for handling a new number is radically
different from the time required for handling a known number, so I'll
assume that test is composed by a mix of unique and non-unique numbers.

Of course I don't have such machine for testing, but for server it was
used a AMD Ryzen 5 PRO 3500U @2.1 GHz and 5 clients were launched in an
AMD A10-7860K @3.6 GHz, both systems with 16 GB RAM. Server was running
Windows 10 and client was running Debian GNU/Linux 11, both java 11 [1].
Network is a home wifi, server with 802.11ac and clients just 802.11g.

In this test each client [2] is sending numbers to the server sequentially
from 0 to the client number * 1000000: first client sends 0 to 1000000,
second sends 0 to 2000000 and so on. Each client sends 6 million numbers
(the count is restarted when the upper limit is reached). This is designed
to generate a lot of new numbers and duplicates in the first million and
decreasing new in the next millions while duplicates rise. These are the
reports for a typical execution of the test:

 Received 45094 unique numbers, 156880 duplicates. Unique total: 45094
 Received 851893 unique numbers, 3121044 duplicates. Unique total: 896987
 Received 914766 unique numbers, 3673848 duplicates. Unique total: 1811753
 Received 1038790 unique numbers, 4136180 duplicates. Unique total: 2850543
 Received 1039666 unique numbers, 4125522 duplicates. Unique total: 3890209
 Received 999516 unique numbers, 3918786 duplicates. Unique total: 4889725
 Received 110275 unique numbers, 4737368 duplicates. Unique total: 5000000
 Received 0 unique numbers, 1130372 duplicates. Unique total: 5000000
 Received 0 unique numbers, 0 duplicates. Unique total: 5000000

These numbers suggest that the application is capable of handling around four
duplicates for each unique number:

  Uniq.   Dupl.   D/U     U+(D/4)  
 ------- ------- ------- --------
   45094  156880 3.47896    84314
  851893 3121044 3.66366  1632154
  914766 3673848 4.01616  1833228
 1038790 4136180 3.98173  2072835
 1039666 4125522 3.96812  2071047
  999516 3918786 3.92068  1979213
  110275 4737368 42.9596  1294617

So, taking this int account, we can argue the peak performance in this
test environment is around ~2M numbers as suggested. Though not much larger
probably because of the lower specs of the involved systems.

